                        <div class="card">
                            <div class="card-header">
                                <h3 class="card-title">Hopewell Furnace's Boarding House</h3>
                            </div>
                            <img src="https://www.nps.gov/common/uploads/structured_data/07E33D3B-1DD8-B71B-0BB0978D03079D7B.jpg" class="card-img-top" alt="Front of Hopewell Furnace's Boarding House" title="Hopewell Furnace's Boarding House housed single men or those living away from their families, who came to work at the furnace." />
                            <div class="card-body">
                                <p>Hopewell Furnace's Boarding House housed single men or those living away from their families, who came to work at the furnace.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class=" col-md-6 col-lg-4 col-xl-3" >
                        <div class="card">
                            <div class="card-header">
                                <h3 class="card-title">Blacksmith Shop & Cast House</h3>
                            </div>
                            <img src="https://www.nps.gov/common/uploads/structured_data/08475132-1DD8-B71B-0B2CA141C1F9566A.jpg" class="card-img-top" alt="Side view of blacksmith shop with cast house behind it." title="The Cast House was the industrial center of the ironworks.  It is were iron ore was smelted into iron metal and products.  The smaller blacksmith shop formed iron metal into all kinds of necessary tools and goods used in everyday life." />
                            <div class="card-body">
                                <p>The Cast House was the industrial center of the ironworks.  It is were iron ore was smelted into iron metal and products.  The smaller blacksmith shop formed iron metal into all kinds of necessary tools and goods used in everyday life.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class=" col-md-6 col-lg-4 col-xl-3" >
                        <div class="card">
                            <div class="card-header">
                                <h3 class="card-title">Hopewell Stove</h3>
                            </div>
                            <img src="https://www.nps.gov/common/uploads/structured_data/08ACB3DD-1DD8-B71B-0B3BBB847B459559.jpg" class="card-img-top" alt="Side view of Hopewell Stove in front of wagon running gear." title="The most notable manufactured product Hopewell Furnace made was its stoves.  They were produced by the thousands at Hopewell and other like furnaces in the early 19th century and were transported for sale by horse and wagon." />
                            <div class="card-body">
                                <p>The most notable manufactured product Hopewell Furnace made was its stoves.  They were produced by the thousands at Hopewell and other like furnaces in the early 19th century and were transported for sale by horse and wagon.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class=" col-md-6 col-lg-4 col-xl-3" >
                        <div class="card">
                            <div class="card-header">
                                <h3 class="card-title">Charcoal Pile</h3>
                            </div>
                            <img src="https://www.nps.gov/common/uploads/structured_data/09205130-1DD8-B71B-0B6D2D12C6918F4D.jpg" class="card-img-top" alt="Demonstration charcoal pile smoldering." title="Charcoal was the fuel used to fire Hopewell Furnace and other furnaces of its age.  Thousands of bushles of charcoal were made from hardwood trees on the furnace lands and entered into the furnace to keep it "in blast."" />
                            <div class="card-body">
                                <p>Charcoal was the fuel used to fire Hopewell Furnace and other furnaces of its age.  Thousands of bushles of charcoal were made from hardwood trees on the furnace lands and entered into the furnace to keep it "in blast."</p>
                            </div>
